segments.text: committed to the values of A&M, including traditions.
By that, I mean sometimes shedding a few tears.
Not treating it just as a academic thing, but a very emotional, because Aggies feel emotional about this group.
It's not just the wise decisions and just an academic framework.
I will always love George W. Bush for the tears he shed when he said goodbye to the state legislature and said,
a job that would cause him to leave Texas.
I will esteem him highly because I love my state too.
I love the University of Texas.
I just see them as two sides of the same apple.
I value loyalty and commitment.
It bothers me when I begin to perceive that they're using people
and using traditions and using things rather than having them being part of their very being.
I would want them, I'm very concerned about bringing in people who are antithetical
That's what A&M stands for.
And I believe there are a lot of them in the campus.
And generally speaking, they're in my area in the liberal arts and in the social studies.
I hate to call them social sciences.
I don't think there is any science or society.
It's an art, not a science.
I've only one time been up in the coffee lounge over there.
I think one time I was told I really wasn't wanted there by somebody who just didn't know who I was.
But Dr. Kramer has invited me to come over there.
Coffee Lounge, where?
Coffee Lounge in the History Building.
Oh.
See, I've been back four and a half years.
I was here 21 years as a member of that department.
I've been invited to only two events in four and a half years back.
They know I'm here kind of.
I call those people missionaries.
that they think they're doing these peasants a favor just by being here.
And then after doing some missionary work here, they will return to the civilized world from where they came and leave us backward savages alone.
I know and I admire many in the athletic department, because I think they've done a good job on the girls' side, because I know that
Girl sports are rife with lesbianism.
Just as I know music departments are rife with homosexuality, male homosexuality.
And I'm sure it will expand to a graduate degree, just as soon as the night follows day, that they'll push for that.
But I'm afraid what it's going to do in the tone of the university.
I guess I'm a troglodyte or something like that, in that many ways.
But I'm an informed troglodyte, or whatever you call it.
I'm a dinosaur.
But I'm willing to change.
I'm willing to evolve.
But I don't want to do it too rapidly.

If you could make a major gift to A&M, if you had the capability to give a million dollars plus, somebody walks up and gives you a check and you've got to pass it on, but you determine the use of that money, for what purpose would you want A&M to use your gift?
It depends on how big it is.
Let's say it's a million dollars plus.
Let me say I had the ability to say that 2,000 young people could go to Texas A&M tuition free, room and board paid, as long as they were in the Corps of Cadets.
I would do it.
The Corps of Cadets could do the same thing that the military academy could do.
How would you select the 2,000 to receive that?
pretty much like the service academies do, have to be open girls.
Number one, academics.
Number two, they would have to have bluttered in some sport, I don't know how far it extends this, or some extracurricular activity, competitive, in high school.
Number three, they would have to go before some kind of a board to have the interpersonal relationship.
And they have to have a great deal of paperwork recommendations.
Because I'm giving them a great deal, a great gift.
And I think that would be one.
To what former students, faculty, staff do you feel most grateful?
To what Aggie-related people do you feel most grateful?
Are there some folks that you now look back and realize that they touched your life?
Roland Bing.
Who?
Roland Bing.
Roland Bing.
I was about to see him after I got my doctorate, just to tell him what I thought of him.
No, see, he was the battalion advisor.
He's an Aggie.
He was here when they started these student publications.
When he started the journalism department while he was here, he wasn't a part of it, I don't think.
Particularly agriculture journalism.
The first time they had journalism here as a major.
Are there others?
Yeah.
Hill.
John Hill?
John Hill.
In history?
In history.
Why was he special?
Made me think.
I thought he was a good scholar.
Mm-hmm.
as opposed to some of the others.
I got very resentful of A&M when I was in advanced course.
I had to write a 30-page monograph on the subject.
And I was totally unprepared to have to write a scholarly paper footnoting bibliography and things.
I never had to do that in my undergraduate work.
When I got where I was in a position to do that in the small Christian college, I made sure that every senior had to write a senior paper
They could use some of their resources, but they had to know the mechanics.
Number two, they also had to go through a senior oral done by professors from other schools.
And because I learned that a lot of kids can't learn to talk when asked a question when they're in a graduate program.
Sure.
What happened after World War I, I knew a fine young man from the University of Texas, William and Mary, who absolutely froze up and
The first person that asked me in my doctorate was, when you think of 18th century Virginia, what do you think of?
You can take anywhere and run anywhere you want to.
Just start.
Don't say, well, I don't know.
You start.
So I just wanted them to learn that in an unthreatening environment.
And so those are the things I did.
the closest to that.
The others were not.
Are there other people to whom you feel grateful?
Colonel Olsen, a wonderful man.
Now let's see, what was his task?
He was the senior branch instructor in infantry last year.
Remember his first name or initials?
O-L-S-E-N?
S-O-N. S-O-N, okay.
I don't know his first name.
First name was Colonel.
What did he teach you?
What did you learn from him?
Leadership, love your troops, care, understanding, defend those that you think need defending.
I mean like giving us advice, imparting wisdom I would say is the greatest thing that he did.
But beyond and outside of ROTC, I think he was part of the wisdom push.
The two people in ROTC are the ones that you're seeing.
John Cook was killed in Korea, from Carrizo Springs in Aggie.
He was somebody I greatly admired and respected.
Colonel Handy.
making the most out of what he had.
Humble, strong but humble.
Saw Colonel Andy go digging out weeds, personally at the track, center track around Kyle Field.
He had to do all of that, and yet he was a wonderful coach, had a world-class track team.
this one and sent it into the Texas Aggie magazine.
The most inspiring moment in sports occurred here when Jerry Bonin, the son of a faculty member, crawled across the finish line of the Southwest Conference trying to beat.
That's the most inspiring thing that I've seen anywhere in sports.
It didn't make world news, national news.
The man just struggled for more than a quarter of a lap to get across the finish line.
That's a good question.
Okay.
All right, I've got only one other question.
Is there any important item we've left out that you have thought of?
Anything we haven't touched on?
Not that I know of.
It'll probably come to me.
Well, and then when we edit it, you can come to it.
All right, then the last question is, what feelings do you carry in your heart for Texas A&M today?
It's complicated, as most things are.
I'm a classical agent.
I value tremendously the memories and the fellowships
I hate, I don't want A&M and I fear that it's turning into just another state university.
We call ourselves Sing Sing on the brasses.
Now the word is fear that it's trying to turn into Berklee on the brasses.
I'd rather be Sing Sing on the brasses with all of the discomfort and everything else than to be Berklee on the brasses.
But I love the school.
I love it because my grandfather loved it.
My father loved it.
My mother loved it.
My brothers were here.
I moved back here from Tennessee.
We had a lovely home over on the hill looking down the thing.
And it was a great move.
My wife says it's the best thing we've ever done, to move back here.
We have great ministry for the Lord here.
So it's just wonderful.
being back here and so many things to do, some of which would not be here if they had him that I admire.
The George Bush Library, went to hear the play club.
One that great?
Yeah, went to Ambrose and Hick when he came here with that group and that thing and though
How did he do that?
How did that happen?
He has people do research for him.
Yeah, yeah.
And also the good ones, they get embarrassed.
Can you summarize that feeling in a sentence or a closing?
It's been memories through my life.
And I've always strove to build good memories.
And I just have the most wonderful memories about A&M.
That's great.
